<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-01-25T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-01-25T05:00:00-05:00" n="73" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d73">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3637: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="#p_CES1" type="from">Cunningham</persName>) to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-01-25T18:00:00+08:00">January 25, 1932—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 8:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>This Consulate General has been informed by <persName corresp="#p_CEY1">Eugene Chen</persName> that both he and <persName corresp="#p_SFK1">Sun Fo</persName> have resigned and that <persName corresp="#p_CK3">Chiang Kai-shek</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_WC1">Wang
                                Ching-wei</persName> are in control at Nanking. He resigned because
                            he claims that <persName corresp="#p_CK3">Chiang Kai-shek</persName>
                            insists on following a passive policy. Had he remained in office Mr.
                                <persName corresp="#p_CEY1">Chen</persName> intended to implement
                            article 16 of the League Covenant.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to the Legation.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_CES1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>